D_Summary.of.lockdown.measures: Libya is also having an ongoing civil war, impacting the nations capacity to respond to the virus. The country’s borders have been closed, large public gatherings banned, and travel restrictions instituted, including between cities. On April 15, the Government of National Accord imposed a 24-hour curfew for a period of 10 days beginning on April 17
The Government has implemented a number of containment measures, including shutting down international borders, closing schools, and implemented a curfew.

On March 28 the Capital, Kabul, went into lockdown where residents were unable to leave their house without a valid  reason. All restaurants, hotels, sauna, cafes, public bathing centers, shrines, gyms, parks and other stores will were closed, with the exceptions of grocery stores and banks. The lockdown was initially planned for 3 weeks, but has been extended. Other cities and provinces are in varying degrees of lockdown, but most have required all but non essential businesses to close.

In March the Government introduced measures to slow the spread of the virus, including banning gatherings of more than 50 people and school closures. On the 30th of March these measures were increased, to include closure of non-essential shops or, where applicable, their reduction in activity - as well as directing the industrial sector toward the production of goods necessary for the prevention and mitigation of the Covid-19 pandemic.
NH_INFORM_Crisis_name: Southern Africa Regional Food Security Crisis

D_Summary.of.lockdown.measures: The  country's largest outbreak has been in the capital, and much of the country's lockdown efforts aim to prevent the spread of the virus from the capital to other regions - through travel restrictions and quarantines. President declared a state of emergency on the 27th of March, and issued a curfew to shorten work hours and ban large gatherings.

The Prime Minister declared a state of emergency on the 8th of April, and implemented more stringent measures, including banning gatherings of more than four people. This ban applies to all religious, governmental, non-governmental, commercial, political and social gatherings. Furthermore, commercial and private employers bound by the Labour proclamation will be prohibited from reducing their workforces or prematurely terminating employment contracts.

The Government has banned international flights and implemented a curfew from  8PM – 6AM. While the Government has encouraged organisations to facilitate working from home, but this remains a suggestion opposed to a mandate.

According to the IMF, the Government has taken a number of actions to slow the spread of the virus. Including a ban on gatherings of more than 15 people, closing schools and public establishments, and restricting movement between cities.

According to the IMF, the Chadian Government has restricted gatherings to no more than 50 people and closed the borders and implemented a curfew from 8PM - 5PM in the main province. Currently, there are few restrictions on businesses.

NH_INFORM_Crisis_name: Southern Africa Regional Food Security Crisis

D_Summary.of.lockdown.measures: The Government shut its borders on the 30th March, and implemented additional lockdown measures on April 10. These include requiring people to wear a mask in public and additional testing facilities. However, many economic activities have continued.
The Government declared a state of emergency on the 24th of March, banning all public gatherings and restricting travel. Restaurants have been closed, as well as religious and sporting facilities.

The IMF reports that, government has restricted travel, shut down schools and banned large public gatherings. Public places (such as religious facilities and businesses) are allowed to remain open if they provide hand sanitiser.
The Government has implemented a curfew, from 7PM to 5AM, banned large gatherings, and suspended international flights.

The Government has developed a preparedness and Response Plan, requiring essential services continuing to function and critical businesses working in shifts. On the 14th of April the resident Mutharika announced a 21-day lockdown, however this was blocked by a high court temporary injunction on the 18th of April.
NH_INFORM_Crisis_name: Southern Africa Regional Food Security Crisis

D_Summary.of.lockdown.measures: The Government has taken a number of measures to respond to the virus, including suspending commercial flights, closing land borders, banning gatherings of more than 50 people, and closing schools, night clubs and bars.

There are variations in the measures different cities and states are implementing to prevent the spread of the virus. A “lockdown” was declared in Lagos, Abuja and Ogun states. Work at home is also encouraged in several states and government institutions while isolation centers are being expanded in Lagos state. Nationally, international airports, public and private schools, universities, stores and markets, have been closed - and public gatherings suspended.

On the 1st of May South Africa moved from a Level 5 (the strictest) to Level 4 Lockdown. During Level 5, only essential businesses were able to operate. At Level 4, restaurants can open for delivery only, mines and factories can reopen - but are restricted with the number of employees they are permitted - and must maintain social distancing amongst workers. Citizens are able to leave their houses once a day, for exercise, but there is a curfew from 8PM to 5AM in which no one can leave.

NH_INFORM_Crisis_name: Southern Africa Regional Food Security Crisis

D_Summary.of.lockdown.measures: The IMF reports thats that government has adopted several containment measures, including social distancing, a nationwide curfew, closure of schools and universities, cancelation of major public events, closure of terrestrial borders, suspension of commercial flights, and quarantine of the affected cities.

The Government has declared a national emergency, with a lockdown imposed from the 21st of April. Most citizens are required to stay at home, although exceptions have been made for grocery stores and major productive and service sectors (manufacturing, food processing, construction, trucking).
The Government has adopted a number of measures, including school closures, travel bans, and closed non-essential retail.
NH_INFORM_Crisis_name: Southern Africa Regional Food Security Crisis

D_Summary.of.lockdown.measures: The Government has introduced a number of measures, including travel restrictions and bans on mass public gatherings. There is currently no national stay at home requirements, although restrictions vary by city. WIth restaurants in Yangon have been instructed to close except for delivery service. Additional movement restrictions have been introduced in 10 Yangon townships: South Okkalapa, Pabedan, Bahan, Mayangone, Insein, Shwe Pyi Thar, Hlaing Tharyar, Mingaladon, Tamwe, and Botahtaung. All residents must stay at home but can leave the house for work. When outside the home residents must wear a mask at all times and carry ID.

The Government has introduced a range of measures to prevent the spread of the virus. Including, international travel restrictions, school and university closures, cancellation and banning of public events, social distancing measures. There are variations between cities and provinces in relation to business closures. With Punjab closing shopping centres and restaurants, but these restrictions not applying nationally, and businesses encouraged to implement social distancing.
The Government has adopted a range of containment measures, including closing borders and a curfew.
Although Angola is in a State of Emergency, they are allowing non-essential commercial and industry activities to operate - in addition to some public services.

The Government has adopted a number of restrictions, with May 22nd a tentative date for lifting them. As part of the restrictions citizens are required to stay at home, movement out of the
home is only restricted to those performing essential services and transporting essential goods. Those permitted to travel will be required to have a COVID-19 TRAVEL PERMIT issued by Government.
The Government has limited business activity to only essential industries, such as health care and food provision - and restricted travel into and within the country.
The Government has ordered the closure of public and private offices, and while many factories have closed, there has not been a government directive.

There has only been limited attempts to control the spread the virus. Borders have remained open, although there are restrictions for people entering from at risk counties. Citizens have been instructed to watch their hands regularly.

According to the IMF, the  Government has restricted gatherings to no more than 20 people and closed the borders and implemented a curfew from 8PM - 5PM in the main province. Currently, there are few restrictions on businesses with the president  explaining that the dominance of the informal economy makes it difficult to implement business restrictions.
The Government has responded by: bans on social gatherings, travel restrictions and a night time curfew. However, there has been minimal impact on economic activity.

A state of emergency was declared on March 27, leading to the closure of all non-essential public and private businesses, with was extended by an additional 45 days on  April 4. Public gatherings are limited to 10 people.

NH_INFORM_Crisis_name: Southern Africa Regional Food Security Crisis

D_Summary.of.lockdown.measures: The Government has taken a number of measures to slow the virus, but not forced the closure of businesses. Many businesses are allowed to remain open, but must adhere to social distancing. There are explicit restrictions on certain types of businesses to promote social distancing, for example makres can open for non-essential items - but must only have 50% of vendors; and restaurants can open during the day, but must close by 7PM.

The Government declared a national state of emergency on the 7th of May, and implemented a range of containment measures. Including travel bans, school closures, a curfew, and restrictions on public gatherings. However, there is not reports of forced business closures.

The Government declared a national state of emergency on the 24th of March, for a period of 12 months. The countries borders have been closed, with flights suspended for three months and land borders restricted. Schools and Universities have been shut down, and public gatherings restricted to 100 people. While businesses have not been forced to shut, there is a national curfew (from 9PM to 7AM) in which everyone must be home and businesses not operating.
The Government has closed restaurants, bars, schools and other places where people may gather. Airports have been closed, and there is screening at land borders.
NH_INFORM_Crisis_name: Southern Africa Regional Food Security Crisis

D_Summary.of.lockdown.measures: The IMF reports that Togo has closed its borders, but does not report on any business restrictions.

On the 24th of March India introduced a national lockdown for 21 days, which has since been extended. As of the 7th of May, the lockdown is planned to be lifted by the 17th of May. With the exception of essential workers, such as healthcare workers and food providers, no one is allowed to leave their home. The Ministry of Home Affairs has stated that people could spend up to a year in jail for failing to abide by the stay at home order.

On March 21st the Government issued a declaration enforcing social distancing, including limiting gatherings to 10 people and closing schools and churches. Banks and restaurants were allowed to continue operations, if people were separated by 5 feet. On the 10th of April the Government announced a state of emergency, and introduced more stringent guidelines - including the closure of al non-essential businesses.

The Government has taken a number of measures to slow the spread of the virus. Travel between cities has been restricted, and within cities restaurants have closed, bars and nightclubs are closed; gatherings of more than 10 people are banned; people are required to maintain distance of at least one meter (three feet) from one another; markets, shops, and other merchants are allowed to remain open, albeit with limited service.

The Government has taken a number of measures to limit the spread of the virus. Including, international travel restrictions, a night time curfew - between 9PM and 5AM, school and business closures. Places in which people gather, such as nightclubs, restaurants, bars and theatres, have been forced to close - although there is not an explicit work from home directive.

A partial lockdown went into effect on the March the 27th, but has begun easing as of May 8, however this did not disrupt economic activity. Those who tested positive for the virus, and anyone they had been in recent contact with, were required to self isolate. However, there have not been restrictions on businesses.

D_Summary.of.lockdown.measures: The Government ordered a partial lockdown of urban areas on the 30th of March, and while this was intended to be lifted on the 23rd of April, as of the 6th of May it continues. The partial lockdown means the closure of schools and banning on public gatherings of more than 25 people - although businesses have not been forced to close. The Government is encouraging people to practice social distancing, wearing masks and washing their hands.
The IMF reports that schools and markets have been closed, but does not mention businesses closures.

The government declared a national state of emergency and adopted containment measures, including social distancing, work from home initiatives (including suspension of the parliament for 21 days), lockdowns in some regions, and travel bans on visitors from high-risk countries, and screening at ports of entry. On the 4th of May travel restrictions were relaxed, to allow travel within the country, but not to allow international travel.
